Let \(\boldsymbol{p} = {(p_1,p_2,\dots,p_n)}^{\top}\) be propensity score and \(\boldsymbol{X} = {(\boldsymbol{x}_1,\boldsymbol{x}_2, \dots, \boldsymbol{x}_n)}^{\top}\) baseline characteristics of subjects in IPD. Also, \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) denotes average vector of baseline characteristics found in SLD. We aim to estimate \(\boldsymbol{p}\) such that \({\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\boldsymbol{X} = {\boldsymbol{\mu}}^{\top}\), i.e. we want to minimize Kullback Leibler divergence of \(\boldsymbol{p}\) and empirical function with some constraints. Specifically, we want to minimize
\[
-{\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\ln(\frac{1}{n\boldsymbol{p}}),
\]
with two constraints:
\[
{\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\boldsymbol{1} = 1, \quad and \quad {\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\boldsymbol{X} = {\boldsymbol{\mu}}^{\top}
\]
We shall use Lagrange Multiplier to solve such an optimization problem as follows.
\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L} &= -{\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\ln(\frac{1}{n\boldsymbol{p}})\boldsymbol{1} - \lambda{({\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\boldsymbol{X} - {\boldsymbol{\mu}}^{\top})}^{\top} \\
&= {\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\ln(n\boldsymbol{p})\boldsymbol{1} - \lambda[( {\boldsymbol{X}}^{\top} - \boldsymbol{\mu}{\boldsymbol{1}}^{\top} )\boldsymbol{p}].
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\]
Above equation could be solved by taking derivative w.r.t \(\boldsymbol{p}\) and \(\lambda\), we then equate both derivations to zero and solve such equations. First, Taking derivative \(\mathcal{L}\) w.r.t \(\lambda\) we obtain
\[
{\boldsymbol{p}}^{\top}\boldsymbol{X} = {\boldsymbol{\mu}}^{\top}.
\tag{2}
\]
Next, taking derivative w.r.t \(p_i\):
\[
\begin{aligned}
&\quad \frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial p_i} = 0 \\
&\Rightarrow \ln(np_i) +n -\lambda(x_i-\mu) = 0 \\
&\Rightarrow \ln(np_i) = \lambda(x_i-\mu)-n \\
&\Rightarrow p_i = \frac{\exp[\lambda(x_i -\mu)-n]}{n} \\
&\Rightarrow p_i = \frac{e^{-n}}{n}\exp[\lambda(x_i-\mu)]
\end{aligned}
\tag{3}
\]
thus,
\[
\begin{aligned}
&\quad 1 = \sum_{i=1}^np_i = \frac{e^{-n}}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\exp[\lambda(x_i-\mu)] \\
& \Rightarrow \frac{n}{e^{-n}} = \sum_{i=1}^n\exp[\lambda(x_i-\mu)]
\end{aligned}
\tag{4}
\]
substitute (4) to (3)`, we obtain

\[\begin{equation}
p_i = \frac{\exp[\lambda(x_i - \mu)]}{\sum_{i=1}^n\exp[\lambda(x_i-\mu)]}
\tag{5}
\end{equation}\]

(5) indicates that \(p_i\) can be estimated by fitting logistic model in which \(z_i= x_i-\mu\) is one covariate, and \(z_i\) must be statisfying (2).
